<HEADLINE>
<P>
SAN DIEGO COUNTY DIGEST: OTAY MESA 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Otay Mesa border crossing was closed for nearly an hour Wednesday by a 
small spill of paint solvent, a county health department official said. 
</P>
<P>
The county's Hazardous Materials Management Team and the Fire Department's 
hazardous unit were called to the port of entry at noon. 
</P>
<P>
Fire officials said traces of paint solvent were found but presented no danger. 
</P>
<P>
A truck, carrying 164, 55-gallon drums was parked at the U.S. Customs 
checkpoint when inspectors discovered the leak, fire officials said. Three 
drums were about one-third full, but only one leaked, said Gary Stephany, 
director of environmental health. 
</P>
<P>
He said that an environmental crime task force will meet to determine if 
charges should be filed against the company for violating federal and state 
laws. 
</P>
<P>
Stephany said the materials were improperly stored, and the truck did not 
display a sign identifying the contents. 
</P>
<P>
The driver, who thought the drums were empty, works for a Mexican trucking 
company, Stephany said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Hazardous materials workers inspect a drum at Otay Mesa border crossing. 
A small spill of paint solvent closed the port of entry for an hour. DAVE 
GATLEY / Los Angeles Times; Photo, CHEMICAL SPILL: Paint solvent leaking from a 
truck closed the Otay Mesa border crossing for nearly an hour. Environmental 
crime task force officials will determine if charges should be filed against 
the trucking company. 
</P>
