<HEADLINE>
<P>
REP. HAWKINS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
It is truly regrettable that Rep. Gus Hawkins (D-Los Angeles) has decided to 
resign after 28 years of fine representation. Hawkins has been a strong and 
powerful advocate for education, health and housing -- the most important 
issues of our times. 
</P>
<P>
His tenure has been unblemished, in contrast to mounting evidence of the 
decline of ethics in government. 
</P>
<P>
As a member of a school board, I am especially sorry to see him go. As chair of 
the House Education &amp; Labor Committee, Hawkins has fought hard to obtain 
more funding and support of educational programs and schools. Just last month, 
he proposed substantial funding in the new federal budget that would have 
nearly doubled federal spending in education. Perhaps the Administration will 
listen, particularly since new studies have shown how effective Head Start, one 
of Hawkins' favorite projects, can be. 
</P>
<P>
Rep. Hawkins will long be known for his efforts to improve the lives of all 
citizens. His shoes are big, but I have no doubt that Assemblywoman Maxine 
Waters (D-Los Angeles), whom you identify as his "heir apparent," will continue 
his tradition. 
</P>
<P>
I'll miss you, Gus. 
</P>
<P>
THOMASINA M. REED 
</P>
<P>
Board of Education Member 
</P>
<P>
Inglewood Unified School District 
</P>
</TEXT>
