<HEADLINE>
<P>
ERMA BOMBECK: MOM 'DOESN'T WORK'? HA! 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ERMA BOMBECK 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
She described herself as a "rare breed who made a conscious decision to stop 
work, stay at home and raise our child." 
</P>
<P>
She went on to say that she's discovered it was a heck of a lot simpler to 
manage an office of 20 employees (10 with PMS) than to be a full-time 
homemaker. 
</P>
<P>
The only problem, she writes, is, "How do you explain to people who ask, 'What 
do you do with yourself all day?' " 
</P>
<P>
It's the oldest question in the world. People never wait around for the answer. 
They probably won't read to the end of this column, but here are some of the 
answers shared by my readers through the years: 
</P>
<P>
Thaw hamburger in the dry cycle of the dishwasher. Worm the dog, play cards 
with a sick child who cheats, dress naked dolls, take phone messages for people 
with a social life, make Christmas ornaments out of lint. Nurse a dead fern 
that cost $20. 
</P>
<P>
* "I spent an entire morning at the hospital when one of my kids swallowed a 
rock," wrote one mother. "When I asked her why, she said she wasn't allowed to 
eat any food before dinner and she was hungry. Surgery is scheduled for 
Monday." 
</P>
<P>
* "We looked everywhere for Marlene's sock. It turned up on the inside of her 
brother's shirt during a social studies test." 
</P>
<P>
* "It took a whole day to clean the stove, but it was worth all the chipping, 
scrubbing and asphyxiation. My husband looked at it and said, 'You missed a 
spot.' " 
</P>
<P>
Cook 2,000 meals a year. Find everything that is lost. Wait for repairmen. Get 
sitters who won't do for minimum what you do for free. Change toilet tissue 
spindle. 
</P>
<P>
* "The policeman pulled me over and said, 'I'm giving you a ticket for no plate 
on your car.' I couldn't believe it until I looked at my son and his friend in 
back. They had been playing gas station with it and didn't put the screws on 
tight." 
</P>
<P>
* "My sons belonged to Little League, and I spent my springs on a lawn chair in 
a field. We ate supper at 4 p.m. and again at 8. I did my Girl Scout work while 
I waited for my sons to be in left field for the one inning they played to miss 
all the balls." 
</P>
<P>
* "I fed the dog a new dog food and he threw up on the new beige carpet and it 
left a hot-pink stain. It took a folder full of correspondence from me to get 
the product off the market." 
</P>
<P>
Make a meat loaf shaped like a heart for Valentine's Day, keep children from 
killing one another, check food daily to see what expired as I slept. Teach 
morality, respect, cleanliness, goodness, and how to say thank you. Drive. 
Drive. Drive. 
</P>
<P>
What do we do all day? Even if people stopped to listen, they wouldn't believe 
it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
