<HEADLINE>
<P>
WHITTIER COLLEGE CAFETERIA BLAZE FORCES STUDENTS TO DINE ALFRESCO 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WHITTIER 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
About 500 students at Whittier College found themselves eating meals on the 
grassy campus lawn and in the faculty lounge this week after a blaze late 
Sunday night destroyed the campus cafeteria. 
</P>
<P>
College officials were expected to hire a catering service to set up a 
temporary cafeteria on a corner of the campus. In the meantime, college cooks 
have been using an outdoor barbecue to prepare food for the students. 
</P>
<P>
Sandra Sarr, a spokeswoman for the college, said fire investigators determined 
that the blaze, which caused about $500,000 damage, was sparked by an 
electrical short in a kitchen refrigerator. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, On Monday morning, workmen set about boarding up windows and sealing off 
the damaged building until repairs could begin. The reflection in the photo at 
right is from a layer of water covering the floor inside the cafeteria. ; 
Photo, Below left, a dishwasher tray is loaded with drinking glasses that 
melted from the heat in the kitchen fire.; Photo, At right, consulting engineer 
Nelson Park surveys the damage in the cafeteria, with its vaulted ceiling, 
before submitting an estimate on the cost of repairs. this has been refilmed 
RICK CORRALES /Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
