<HEADLINE>
<P>
BOYS' SOCCER PLAYOFFS; 
</P>
<P>
KENNEDY, DEFENSE STOP MANUAL ARTS COLD, 1-0 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DANNY SCHUMACHER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Kennedy High scored early and then controlled the ball for the rest of the 
match Wednesday, defeating visiting Manual Arts, 1-0, in a first-round City 
Section contest. 
</P>
<P>
Luis Sandoval gave the Golden Cougars the only goal they would need, heading in 
a corner kick from Brian Singer less than five minutes into the match. 
</P>
<P>
The Toilers' quickness gave Kennedy trouble at times but the Golden Cougars 
managed to stay in control, outshooting Manual Arts, 19-6. 
</P>
<P>
Blustery winds hampered play but Kennedy proved more adept at passing the ball. 
</P>
<P>
"Considering the wind, I thought we played really well," Kennedy Coach Fred 
Singer said. 
</P>
<P>
Manual Arts' scoring opportunities were limited and the Kennedy defense stopped 
any serious threats. 
</P>
<P>
Defender Ruben Rios came up with a big play late in the first half, clearing 
out a Manual Arts shot after goalkeeper Salvador Aragon had left the goal. 
</P>
<P>
Aragon had replaced starting goalkeeper Chris Hines, who is sidelined because 
of a collapsed lung. DANNY SCHUMACHER 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Slide by slide -- Manual Arts' Oscar Recinos, left, and Kennedy's Brian 
Singer tangle during the Golden Cougars' 1-0 soccer playoff victory. MEL MELCON 
/ for The Times 
</P>
